mment": "Fixed typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_Tolstoy"}
{"title_page": "Chester County Historical Society", "text_new": "{{Infobox Museum\n |name        = Chester County Historical Society Headquarters\n |image       = Chester County PA Hist Soc.JPG\n |image_upright =\n |map_type    =\n |established = 1893\n |location    = 225 North High Street<br />[[West Chester, Pennsylvania|West Chester]], [[Pennsylvania]] \n |type        = Historical/Museum\n |visitors    = \n |director    = \n |curator     = \n |website     = {{url|http://www.chestercohistorical.org}}\n{{Infobox NRHP | name =Horticultural Hall\n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes\n  | built = 1848<ref name=\"arch\">{{cite web| url = https://www.dot7.state.pa.us/ce/SelectWelcome.asp| title = National Historic Landmarks & National Register of Historic Places in Pennsylvania| publisher = CRGIS: Cultural Resources Geographic Information System| format = Searchable database}}''Note:'' This includes {{cite web| url = {{NRHP-PA|H077436_01H.pdf}}| title = National Register of Historic Places Nomination Form: West Chester Downtown Historic | accessdate = 2012-11-05| author =Ray H. Ott, Jr.| format = PDF| date=October 1984}}</ref>\n  | architect = [[Thomas U. Walter]]\n  | designated_nrhp_type  = July 2, 1985\n  | partof = [[West Chester Downtown Historic District]]\n  | partof_refnum = 85001447<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Chester County Historical Society''' is a [[non-profit organization|non-profit]] [[historical society]], founded in 1893, dedicated to collecting, preserving, and exhibiting the history of [[Chester County, Pennsylvania|Chester County]], [[Pennsylvania]] and the surrounding area.  The Historical Society is located at 225 North High Street in downtown [[West Chester, Pennsylvania|West Chester]].\n\n==History==\nDr. [[Robert Lukens]] served as the President of the Chester County Historical Society from 2011 until 2015.<ref name=pinquirer>{{cite news|first=Cat |last=Coyle |title=Robert D. Lukens, 42, president of Chester County Historical Society |url=http://articles.philly.com/2015-08-06/news/65247890_1_ellen-endslow-chester-county-historical-society-county-history |work=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=2015-08-06 |accessdate=2015-09-01}}</ref> Lukens oversaw the renovations and beautification of the society's buildings and other facilities.<ref name=pinquirer/> He acquired state grants for the society and published a historical column in the ''[[Daily Local News]]''.<ref name=pinquirer/>\n\n==Building==\n[[File:Historic American Buildings Survey, Ned Goode, Photographer June, 1958 RECESSED ARCH, WEST FRONT. - Chester County Horticultural Hall, 225 North High Street, West Chester, Chester HABS PA,15-WCHES,4-2.tif|thumb|Horticultural Hall in 1958]]The History Center is a 56,000-square-foot complex that houses the historical society. It includes two connected buildings.\n\nThe older building, known as Horticultural Hall, was designed by renowned architect [[Thomas U. Walter]] in 1848. It was the site of the 1852 Pennsylvania Women's Rights convention.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Young|first1=Robyn|title=The 1852 Women's Rights Convention at Horticultural Hall in West Chester|url=http://www.chestercountyhospital.org/cchfdn.asp?p=1488&m=1466|website=Chester County Day|accessdate=August 25, 2016|date=October 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010122146/http://www.chestercountyhospital.org/cchfdn.asp?p=1488&m=1466|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=dead}} Note that the pages are store by year, click \"2015\"</ref>\n\nThe buildings were modernized in 1979 and contain over 500,000 manuscripts, 80,000 photographs, and 20,000 volumes. The [[National Register of Historic Places]] named West Chester one of \"America's Dozen Distinctive Destinations\" in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.chestercohistorical.org/about|website=Chester County Historical Society|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[File:Historic American Buildings Survey, PHOTOCOPY 1870'S. - Chester County Horticultural Hall, 225 North High Street, West Chester, Chester County, PA HABS PA,15-WCHES,4-4.tif|thumb|upright=1.3|Horticultural Hall in the 1870s]][[List of historical societies]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{commons category-inline|Horticultural Hall (West Chester, Pennsylvania)}}\n* [http://www.chestercohistorical.org Official Web Site].\n{{West Chester, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Mid-Atlantic U.S. historical societies}}\n\n[[Category:1893 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Historical societies in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:History museums in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:West Chester, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Thomas U. Walter buildings]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Chester County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Museums in Chester County, Pennsylvania]]\n\n{{US-org-stub}}\n{{hist-org-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Museum\n |name        = Chester County Historical Society Headquarters\n |image       = Chester County PA Hist Soc.JPG\n |image_upright =\n |map_type    =\n |established = 1893\n |location    = 225 North High Street<br />[[West Chester, Pennsylvania|West Chester]], [[Pennsylvania]] \n |type        = Historical/Museum\n |visitors    = \n |director    = \n |curator     = \n |website     = {{url|http://www.chestercohistorical.org}}\n{{Infobox NRHP | name =Horticultural Hall\n  | embed = yes\n  | nrhp_type = cp | nocat = yes\n  | built = 1848<ref name=\"arch\">{{cite web| url = https://www.dot7.state.pa.us/ce/SelectWelcome.asp| title = National Historic Landmarks & National Register of Historic Places in Pennsylvania| publisher = CRGIS: Cultural Resources Geographic Information System| format = Searchable database}}''Note:'' This includes {{cite web| url = {{NRHP-PA|H077436_01H.pdf}}| title = National Register of Historic Places Nomination Form: West Chester Downtown Historic | accessdate = 2012-11-05| author =Ray H. Ott, Jr.| format = PDF| date=October 1984}}</ref>\n  | architect = [[Thomas U. Walter]]\n  | designated_nrhp_type  = July 2, 1985\n  | partof = [[West Chester Downtown Historic District]]\n  | partof_refnum = 85001447<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|version=2010a}}</ref>\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Chester County Historical Society''' is a [[non-profit organization|non-profit]] [[historical society]], founded in 1893, dedicated to collecting, preserving, and exhibiting the history of [[Chester County, Pennsylvania|Chester County]], [[Pennsylvania]] and the surrounding area.  The Historical Society is located at 225 North High Street in downtown [[West Chester, Pennsylvania|West Chester]].\n\n==History==\nDr. [[Robert Lukens]] served as the President of the Chester County Historical Society from 2011 until 2015.<ref name=pinquirer>{{cite news|first=Cat |last=Coyle |title=Robert D. Lukens, 42, president of Chester County Historical Society |url=http://articles.philly.com/2015-08-06/news/65247890_1_ellen-endslow-chester-county-historical-society-county-history |work=[[Philadelphia Inquirer]] |date=2015-08-06 |accessdate=2015-09-01}}</ref> Lukens oversaw the renovations and beautification of the society's buildings and other facilities.<ref name=pinquirer/> He acquired state grants for the society and published a historical column in the ''[[Daily Local News]]''.<ref name=pinquirer/>\n\n==Building==\n[[File:Historic American Buildings Survey, PHOTOCOPY 1870'S. - Chester County Horticultural Hall, 225 North High Street, West Chester, Chester County, PA HABS PA,15-WCHES,4-4.tif|thumb|upright=1.3|Horticultural Hall in the 1870s]]\nThe History Center is a 56,000-square-foot complex that houses the historical society. It includes two connected buildings.\n\nThe older building, known as Horticultural Hall, was designed by renowned architect [[Thomas U. Walter]] in 1848. It was the site of the 1852 Pennsylvania Women's Rights convention.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Young|first1=Robyn|title=The 1852 Women's Rights Convention at Horticultural Hall in West Chester|url=http://www.chestercountyhospital.org/cchfdn.asp?p=1488&m=1466|website=Chester County Day|accessdate=August 25, 2016|date=October 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010122146/http://www.chestercountyhospital.org/cchfdn.asp?p=1488&m=1466|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=dead}} Note that the pages are store by year, click \"2015\"</ref>\n\nThe buildings were modernized in 1979 and contain over 500,000 manuscripts, 80,000 photographs, and 20,000 volumes. The [[National Register of Historic Places]] named West Chester one of \"America's Dozen Distinctive Destinations\" in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=About|url=http://www.chestercohistorical.org/about|website=Chester County Historical Society|accessdate=31 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n*[[File:Historic American Buildings Survey, Ned Goode, Photographer June, 1958 RECESSED ARCH, WEST FRONT. - Chester County Horticultural Hall, 225 North High Street, West Chester, Chester HABS PA,15-WCHES,4-2.tif|thumb|Horticultural Hall in 1958]][[List of historical societies]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{commons category-inline|Horticultural Hall (West Chester, Pennsylvania)}}\n* [http://www.chestercohistorical.org Official Web Site].\n{{West Chester, Pennsylvania}}\n{{Mid-Atlantic U.S. historical societies}}\n\n[[Category:1893 establishments in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Historical societies in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:History museums in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:West Chester, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Thomas U. Walter buildings]]\n[[Category:Historic district contributing properties in Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Chester County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Museums in Chester County, Pennsylvania]]\n\n{{US-org-stub}}\n{{hist-org-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Kire1975", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chester_County_Historical_Society"}
{"title_page": "Howie Severino", "text_new": "{{Philippine name|Gorospe|Severino}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Howie Severino\n| image              = Howie Severino - 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Severino in January 2018\n| birth_name         = Horacio Gorospe Severino\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1961|7|18|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]\n| occupation         = Journalist\n| spouse             = Ipat Luna\n| children           = Alon Severino\n| education          = [[Tufts University]] <br> [[University of Sussex]]\n| television         = ''[[i-Witness]]'' host <br>''[[News to Go]]'' anchor\n| yearsactive        = 1988-present\n| parents            = Amb. Rodolfo Severino and Tati Gorospe Severino\n| awards             = [[PMPC Star Awards for TV]] <br> Rotary Journalism Awards\n}}\n'''Horacio \"Howie\" Gorospe Severino''' (born July 18, 1961) is a [[Philippines|Filipino]] broadcast journalist best known for his work with the [[Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism]], the [[Probe (Philippine TV series)|Probe Team]], and the [[GMA Network]]. He has worked in print, television, and online media.\n\n==Background==\n\n===Education===\nHe said he has wanted to be a journalist ever since he was in fifth grade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsflash.org/2004/02/sb/sb004228.htm|title=Howie Severino: The Quintessential Journalist|author=Alma Anonas-Carpio|date=17 August 2006|publisher=[[Philippine Star]]|accessdate=18 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120602150244/http://www.newsflash.org/2004/02/sb/sb004228.htm|archivedate=2 June 2012}}</ref> He graduated from [[Tufts University]] in [[Massachusetts]] with a History degree, ''[[magna cum laude]]'', and received his master's degree from [[University of Sussex]] in the [[United Kingdom]] in Environment, Development, and Policy.\n\nAs a college student in [[Boston]] in the early 1980s, he got to know [[Ninoy Aquino|Benigno Aquino, Jr.]], then in exile. After Aquino's assassination in 1983, Severino returned home to teach at his alma mater Ateneo High School, and join the anti-Marcos movement. He was arrested on the same day as [[Lino Brocka]] and [[Behn Cervantes]] and detained for eight days in [[Fort Bonifacio]], which was at the time a dreaded army camp and not yet the high-end real estate development hub that it is today.\n\n===Career===\nSeverino started as a newspaper reporter and magazine writer in 1988; became a co-founder of the [[Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism]] (PCIJ); established himself as a leading documentary filmmaker; and, in 2009, was named Editor-in-Chief of GMA News Online, [[GMA Network]]'s news website. He stepped down in 2014 after five years, and was appointed GMA Network's Vice President for Professional Development in May 2014.\n\nOn TV, he was on ''[[Probe (Philippine TV series)|Probe Team]]'' for four years with [[Cheche Lazaro]] before joining ''[[i-Witness]]'', now one of the longest-running public affairs programs in the Philippines.\n\nAt the PCIJ, he set up the Center's Environment Desk, built credentials as a leading environmental journalist, and worked closely with [[Ramon Magsaysay Award|Ramon Magsaysay]] awardee [[Sheila Coronel]]. He still produces environmental documentaries for ''i-Witness'' and often appears on television riding his mountain bike.\n\nOnline, he was the first blogger on GMA's web platforms. His journalistic exploration of emerging media culminated in 2009 with his appointment as GMA Network's Vice President for Multimedia Journalism<ref name=\"NewVPforMultimedia\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/60-media/57258-howie-severino-new-post |title=GMA-7 announces new post for Howie Severino |date=2014-05-05 |work=Rappler |access-date=2019-10-18 |language=en}}{{Cite news |url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/60-media/57258-howie-severino-new-post |title=GMA-7 announces new post for Howie Severino |date=2014-05-05 |work=Rappler |access-date=2019-10-18 |language=en}}</ref> and his subsequent assignment to helm GMA News Online.\n\nAs GMA News Online's Editor-in-Chief, Severino and his team pioneered in the Philippines the use of [[Google Maps]] for disaster coverage, [[Twitter]] for breaking news, and crowd-sourcing for news gathering.\n\nIn 2011, Severino became co-anchor of the morning television show ''[[News to Go]]'' on [[GMA News TV]], alongside [[Kara David]].\n\n===Personal life===\nSeverino's parents are Ambassador [[Rodolfo Severino Jr.]], former secretary-general of the [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations]] (ASEAN) from 1998 to 2002, and Tati Gorospe Severino. a former schoolteacher and administrator.\n\nSeverino is married to Ipat Luna, an environmental lawyer and TOYM awardee, with whom he has a son, Alon Roberto. In 2012, Alon, 10, was named Best Child Performer by the Aliw Awards for his role in Totong Hilot, a play staged in the Cultural Center of the Philippines during the Virgin Labfest. \n\nOn April 7, 2020, it was revealed that Severino was the 2828th [[COVID-19]] patient during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/07/second-headline/veteran-broadcast-journalist-howie-severino-covid-19-survivor/710962/|title=Veteran broadcast journalist Howie Severino, 'Covid-19 survivor'|last=Iglesias|first=Iza|date=2020-04-07|website=The Manila Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> He later recovered from the coronavirus after being in the hospital for seven days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/specials/content/140/howie-severino-i-am-covid-19-patient-2828/|title=Howie Severino: I am COVID-19 Patient 2828|last=Severino|first=Howie|date=April 7, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> A special ''[[i-Witness]]'' documentary about his experience as a COVID-positive patient; entitled ''Ako si Patient 2828'', aired on [[GMA Network|GMA]] on April 18, 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2020/04/17/2007974/ako-si-patient-2828-howie-severino-shares-covid-19-bout-i-witness-documentary|title='Ako si Patient 2828': Howie Severino shares COVID-19 bout in 'i-Witness' documentary|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel|date=April 17, 2020|website=Philstar.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and citations==\n{{refimprove|date=June 2018|section}}\nSeverino is one of the Philippines' most awarded journalists. His awards include:\n\n*Neil Davis Award given to one young Asia-Pacific journalist, 1991\n*CMMA best newspaper reporter, 1991\n*Jaime V Ongpin Grand Prize, Investigative reporting, 1996\n*Four-time winner of Rotary Club of Manila's Journalist of the Year awards\n*Three-time winner of UPLB's Gandingan awards (Best Documentarist)\n*Titus Brandsma Award for Leadership in Journalism, 2009\n*PUP's Mabini Award for Media\n*PUP's MARINGAL NA PANTAS award for contributions to historical studies, 2012\n*PHL Medical Association's Rizal award for documentaries on Rizal\n*Adamson's first Adamson Univ. Media Award, 2011\n*La Sallian Scholarum Award for Best TV feature for youth, 2005\n\nIn 2007, Severino was inducted to the Rotary Club of Manila's Journalism Hall of Fame<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.gmanews.tv/sidetrip/blog/archives/248-Gratitude.html|title=Gratitude|author=Howie Severino|date=21 June 2007|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> after he was named [[Journalist|Broadcast Journalist]] of the Year twice and [[Investigative journalism|Investigative Journalist]] of the Year twice.\n\nIn October 2007, GMA Network released ''Ten Years of Howie Severino'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gmarecordscatalog.blogspot.com/2012/03/ten-years-of-howie-severino.html|title=Ten Years of Howie Severino|date=30 March 2012|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|accessdate=18 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121203202952/http://gmarecordscatalog.blogspot.com/2012/03/ten-years-of-howie-severino.html|archivedate=3 December 2012}}</ref> a DVD compilation of ten of his most notable documentaries. Included on the DVD was ''Huling Hala-bira'', a documentary about a family living under the railroad tracks in [[Pandacan, Manila]], which won second prize that same year in a [[United Nations]]-sponsored international broadcast competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/899/quoti-witnessquot-documentary-festivals-takes-place-on-july-21-and-28|title=\"I-Witness\" Documentary Festivals takes place on July 21 and 28|author=Jocelyn Dimaculangan|date=18 July 2007|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2009 trust survey conducted by ''[[Reader's Digest]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/247821/gma-news-pillars-among-reader-s-digest-s-most-trusted-filipinos|title=Reader's Digest's 'Most Trusted Filipinos'|date=15 March 2010|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|accessdate=18 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111130105654/http://mb.com.ph/articles/247821/gma-news-pillars-among-reader-s-digest-s-most-trusted-filipinos|archivedate=30 November 2011}}</ref> Severino was sixth on a list of most trusted Filipinos.\n\n''People Asia Magazine'', in its June\u2013July 2012 issue,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lape\u00f1a|first=Carmela|title=Howie Severino one of People Asia's 'Men Who Matter'|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/263448/lifestyle/people/howie-severino-one-of-people-asia-s-men-who-matter|publisher=GMA News Online|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> named Severino one of that year's \"Men Who Matter\".\n\n==See also==\n*[[GMA News and Public Affairs]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{facebook|Howieseverino}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Severino, Horacio G}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Filipino educators]]\n[[Category:Filipino activists]]\n[[Category:Ateneo de Manila University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Sussex]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:People from Manila]]\n[[Category:GMA News and Public Affairs people]]\n[[Category:Filipino television journalists]]\n", "text_old": "{{Philippine name|Gorospe|Severino}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Howie Severino\n| image              = Howie Severino - 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size         = \n| caption            = Severino in January 2018\n| birth_name         = Horacio Gorospe Severino\n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1961|7|18|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Manila]], [[Philippines]]\n| occupation         = Journalist\n| spouse             = Ipat Luna\n| children           = Alon Severino\n| education          = [[Tufts University]] <br> [[University of Sussex]]\n| television         = ''[[i-Witness]]'' host <br>''[[News to Go]]'' anchor\n| yearsactive        = 1988-present\n| parents            = Amb. Rodolfo Severino and Tati Gorospe Severino\n| awards             = [[PMPC Star Awards for TV]] <br> Rotary Journalism Awards\n}}\n'''Horacio \"Howie\" Gorospe Severino''' (born July 18, 1961) is a [[Philippines|Filipino]] broadcast journalist best known for his work with the [[Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism]], the [[Probe (Philippine TV series)|Probe Team]], and the [[GMA Network]]. He has worked in print, television, and online media.\n\n==Background==\n\n===Education===\nHe said he has wanted to be a journalist ever since he was in fifth grade.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsflash.org/2004/02/sb/sb004228.htm|title=Howie Severino: The Quintessential Journalist|author=Alma Anonas-Carpio|date=17 August 2006|publisher=[[Philippine Star]]|accessdate=18 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120602150244/http://www.newsflash.org/2004/02/sb/sb004228.htm|archivedate=2 June 2012}}</ref> He graduated from [[Tufts University]] in [[Massachusetts]] with a History degree, ''[[magna cum laude]]'', and received his master's degree from [[University of Sussex]] in the [[United Kingdom]] in Environment, Development, and Policy.\n\nAs a college student in [[Boston]] in the early 1980s, he got to know [[Ninoy Aquino|Benigno Aquino, Jr.]], then in exile. After Aquino's assassination in 1983, Severino returned home to teach at his alma mater Ateneo High School, and join the anti-Marcos movement. He was arrested on the same day as [[Lino Brocka]] and [[Behn Cervantes]] and detained for eight days in [[Fort Bonifacio]], which was at the time a dreaded army camp and not yet the high-end real estate development hub that it is today.\n\n===Career===\nSeverino started as a newspaper reporter and magazine writer in 1988; became a co-founder of the [[Philippine Center for Investigative Journalism]] (PCIJ); established himself as a leading documentary filmmaker; and, in 2009, was named Editor-in-Chief of GMA News Online, [[GMA Network]]'s news website. He stepped down in 2014 after five years, and was appointed GMA Network's Vice President for Professional Development in May 2014.\n\nOn TV, he was on ''[[Probe (Philippine TV series)|Probe Team]]'' for four years with [[Cheche Lazaro]] before joining ''[[i-Witness]]'', now one of the longest-running public affairs programs in the Philippines.\n\nAt the PCIJ, he set up the Center's Environment Desk, built credentials as a leading environmental journalist, and worked closely with [[Ramon Magsaysay Award|Ramon Magsaysay]] awardee [[Sheila Coronel]]. He still produces environmental documentaries for ''i-Witness'' and often appears on television riding his mountain bike.\n\nOnline, he was the first blogger on GMA's web platforms. His journalistic exploration of emerging media culminated in 2009 with his appointment as GMA Network's Vice President for Multimedia Journalism<ref name=\"NewVPforMultimedia\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/60-media/57258-howie-severino-new-post |title=GMA-7 announces new post for Howie Severino |date=2014-05-05 |work=Rappler |access-date=2019-10-18 |language=en}}{{Cite news |url=http://www.rappler.com/nation/60-media/57258-howie-severino-new-post |title=GMA-7 announces new post for Howie Severino |date=2014-05-05 |work=Rappler |access-date=2019-10-18 |language=en}}</ref> and his subsequent assignment to helm GMA News Online.\n\nAs GMA News Online's Editor-in-Chief, Severino and his team pioneered in the Philippines the use of [[Google Maps]] for disaster coverage, [[Twitter]] for breaking news, and crowd-sourcing for news gathering.\n\nIn 2011, Severino became co-anchor of the morning television show ''[[News to Go]]'' on [[GMA News TV]], alongside [[Kara David]].\n\n===Personal life===\nSeverino's parents are Ambassador [[Rodolfo Severino Jr.]], former secretary-general of the [[Association of Southeast Asian Nations]] (ASEAN) from 1998 to 2002, and Tati Gorospe Severino. a former schoolteacher and administrator.\n\nSeverino is married to Ipat Luna, an environmental lawyer and TOYM awardee, with whom he has a son, Alon Roberto. In 2012, Alon, 10, was named Best Child Performer by the Aliw Awards for his role in Totong Hilot, a play staged in the Cultural Center of the Philippines during the Virgin Labfest. \n\nOn April 7, 2020, it was revealed that Severino is the 2828th [[COVID-19]] patient during the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/07/second-headline/veteran-broadcast-journalist-howie-severino-covid-19-survivor/710962/|title=Veteran broadcast journalist Howie Severino, 'Covid-19 survivor'|last=Iglesias|first=Iza|date=2020-04-07|website=The Manila Times|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> He later recovered from the coronavirus after being in the hospital for seven days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/specials/content/140/howie-severino-i-am-covid-19-patient-2828/|title=Howie Severino: I am COVID-19 Patient 2828|last=Severino|first=Howie|date=April 7, 2020|website=GMA News Online|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-07}}</ref> A special [[i-Witness]] documentary about his experience as a COVID-positive patient; entitled ''Ako si Patient 2828'', aired on [[GMA Network|GMA]] on April 18, 2020. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2020/04/17/2007974/ako-si-patient-2828-howie-severino-shares-covid-19-bout-i-witness-documentary|title='Ako si Patient 2828': Howie Severino shares COVID-19 bout in 'i-Witness' documentary|last=San Juan|first=Ratziel|date=April 17, 2020|website=Philstar.com|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and citations==\n{{refimprove|date=June 2018|section}}\nSeverino is one of the Philippines' most awarded journalists. His awards include:\n\n*Neil Davis Award given to one young Asia-Pacific journalist, 1991\n*CMMA best newspaper reporter, 1991\n*Jaime V Ongpin Grand Prize, Investigative reporting, 1996\n*Four-time winner of Rotary Club of Manila's Journalist of the Year awards\n*Three-time winner of UPLB's Gandingan awards (Best Documentarist)\n*Titus Brandsma Award for Leadership in Journalism, 2009\n*PUP's Mabini Award for Media\n*PUP's MARINGAL NA PANTAS award for contributions to historical studies, 2012\n*PHL Medical Association's Rizal award for documentaries on Rizal\n*Adamson's first Adamson Univ. Media Award, 2011\n*La Sallian Scholarum Award for Best TV feature for youth, 2005\n\nIn 2007, Severino was inducted to the Rotary Club of Manila's Journalism Hall of Fame<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.gmanews.tv/sidetrip/blog/archives/248-Gratitude.html|title=Gratitude|author=Howie Severino|date=21 June 2007|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref> after he was named [[Journalist|Broadcast Journalist]] of the Year twice and [[Investigative journalism|Investigative Journalist]] of the Year twice.\n\nIn October 2007, GMA Network released ''Ten Years of Howie Severino'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gmarecordscatalog.blogspot.com/2012/03/ten-years-of-howie-severino.html|title=Ten Years of Howie Severino|date=30 March 2012|publisher=[[GMA Network]]|accessdate=18 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://archive.is/20121203202952/http://gmarecordscatalog.blogspot.com/2012/03/ten-years-of-howie-severino.html|archivedate=3 December 2012}}</ref> a DVD compilation of ten of his most notable documentaries. Included on the DVD was ''Huling Hala-bira'', a documentary about a family living under the railroad tracks in [[Pandacan, Manila]], which won second prize that same year in a [[United Nations]]-sponsored international broadcast competition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pep.ph/guide/tv/899/quoti-witnessquot-documentary-festivals-takes-place-on-july-21-and-28|title=\"I-Witness\" Documentary Festivals takes place on July 21 and 28|author=Jocelyn Dimaculangan|date=18 July 2007|publisher=[[Philippine Entertainment Portal]]|accessdate=18 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn a 2009 trust survey conducted by ''[[Reader's Digest]]'' magazine,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mb.com.ph/articles/247821/gma-news-pillars-among-reader-s-digest-s-most-trusted-filipinos|title=Reader's Digest's 'Most Trusted Filipinos'|date=15 March 2010|publisher=[[Manila Bulletin]]|accessdate=18 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111130105654/http://mb.com.ph/articles/247821/gma-news-pillars-among-reader-s-digest-s-most-trusted-filipinos|archivedate=30 November 2011}}</ref> Severino was sixth on a list of most trusted Filipinos.\n\n''People Asia Magazine'', in its June\u2013July 2012 issue,<ref>{{cite web|last=Lape\u00f1a|first=Carmela|title=Howie Severino one of People Asia's 'Men Who Matter'|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/263448/lifestyle/people/howie-severino-one-of-people-asia-s-men-who-matter|publisher=GMA News Online|accessdate=20 September 2012}}</ref> named Severino one of that year's \"Men Who Matter\".\n\n==See also==\n*[[GMA News and Public Affairs]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{facebook|Howieseverino}}\n*{{Twitter}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Severino, Horacio G}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Filipino educators]]\n[[Category:Filipino activists]]\n[[Category:Ateneo de Manila University alumni]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Sussex]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:People from Manila]]\n[[Category:GMA News and Public Affairs people]]\n[[Category:Filipino television journalists]]\n", "name_user": "RonanWildcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Howie_Severino"}
{"title_page": "Agomani", "text_new": "{{About|the town in Dhubri District|its namesake district|Dhubri district}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{confusing|date=January 2015}}\n{{essay-like|date=January 2015}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2015}}\n}}\n\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Agomani\n| other_name                      = \n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = Town\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Assam#India\n| pushpin_label_position          = \n| pushpin_map_alt                 = \n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Assam, India\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|26.199|N|89.785|E|display=inline,title|format=dms}}\n| subdivision_type                = [[Country]]\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Assam]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Dhubri district|Dhubri]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                = \n| founder                         = \n| named_for                       = \n| government_type                 = \n| governing_body                  = \n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  = \n| area_rank                       = \n| area_total_km2                  = 4\n| elevation_footnotes             = \n| elevation_m                     = \n| population_total                = \n| population_as_of                = As On 1991 Census Report\n| population_rank                 = \n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_demonym              = \n| population_footnotes            = \n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Assamese language|Assamese]]\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = [http://pincode.net.in/783335_PINCODE 783335]\n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:IN|IN-AS]]\n| registration_plate              = AS 17\n| website                         = \n| footnotes                       = \n}}\n\n'''Agomani''' is a small town area of [[Dhubri district]] ([[Assam]]) [[India]]. It is an area on the bank of [[Gangadhar River]] with historical significance. Agomani stands in a rural area, but it is not a revenue village. Some portions of the village of Kaldoba and Shernagar formed the small area of Agomani. The area of Agomani is about 4&nbsp;km<sup>2</sup> Agomani is situated at a distance of 50&nbsp;km to the North West of [[Dhubri]], 12&nbsp;km to the South of West Bengal border and 8&nbsp;km to the North East of Bangladesh border. [[National Highway 17 (India)|National Highway 17]] passes through Agomani from North to South and the historical [[Gohain Kamal Ali]] (Road) runs from East to West. Both the roads crossed it the heart of Agomani. At the conjunction, there is a daily market and shops of all kinds are established. In 1963 a terrible Cyclone blew over Agomani and swept away many houses, lives and properties and the name of Agomani appeared on Newspaper, Radio & T.V and Agomani had been known to all over Assam.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cic.nic.in/cicwebpages/Assam/agomani/agmhistory.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=27 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20041227195138/http://www.cic.nic.in/cicwebpages/Assam/agomani/agmhistory.html |archive-date=27 December 2004 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nAgomani is an important place with some historical background. It is situated in the district of [[Dhubri]] ([[Assam]]). There are some sayings about the origin of the name of AGOMANI. Agomani derives from the word '''\"AGOMAN\"'''which means arrival. It is said that Mahapurush Sri Sri  Shankardeva, the great preacher of the Bhagawati Bhaishnava faith, made a voyage from Pathbaushi with his niece Aai Bhubeneshwari to get her marriage with Chillarai, the brother of Nara Narayana, the king of Koch kingdom. They made a journey by boat on the river Ganghadhar. Both of them arrived at Agomani Ghat and received each other. From that time the place was named Agomani. Later Shankardeva and Chilarai came to Satrasal where marriage ceremony of Aai Bhubeneshwari with Chilarai was performed. (which is controversial)\nThere are other sayings that Raja Probhat Ch. Baruah, the Jamindar of Gouripur and Maharaja Nara Narayana, the King of Koch kingdom arrived at the place of Agomani to meet and to settle some disputes overland. To commemorate that historical meeting, the place has been known as Agomani.\n\n== Demographics ==\nAgomani is a thickly populated area. Most of the inhabitants are cultivators. There are some service holders and Business men also. Cultivators produced rice, jute, wheat, vegetable and other agricultural crops. But the economic condition of the general people of Agomani is good. This is due to the fact that the most of the people belong to the backward classes. Residences of Agomani are mostly Hindus and Muslims. They are peace-loving people and have been living in communal harmony and peace since long ago. There was no record of communal disturbances at Agomani.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cic.nic.in/cicwebpages/Assam/agomani/festival.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=26 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303233455/http://www.cic.nic.in/cicwebpages/Assam/agomani/festival.html |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cic.nic.in/cicwebpages/Assam/agomani/frame3.html |title=\"Agomani Development Block\" |access-date=26 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052309/http://www.cic.nic.in/cicwebpages/Assam/agomani/frame3.html |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Sheelbhadra the famous Assamese writer, wrote a novel namely \"AGOMANIR GHAT\" which made Agomani well known.\n\n== Facilities ==\nThere are several Govt. Offices and Institutions are in and around Agomani these are \u2013 A.S.O and Circle Office, B.D.O and CIC Office, S.D.O ASEB Office, Post Office, Couriers Facilities - Ecom Express, Blue Dart(DHL), Ekart Logistics, Handloom and Textile Office, S.O, P.W.D Office, Telephone Exchange, P.H.C. and Hospitals, UCO Bank, State Bank Of India, Bandhan Bank, Pragati College, Agomani H.S. School, Agomani J.B. School, Girls high and M.E. School, Indoor Stadium, Basketball Court, and Agomani Mini Stadium etc. These offices and Institutions increased the importance of Agomani and It is going to form a small town-ship. There is a big Bi-Weekly market at a distance of half a kilometre to the West called kaldoba haat (market). It is a business place. The [[Gangadhar river]] flowing towards the Brahmaputra is at a distance of half a kilometre to the east to the Agomani. The famous \"Agomani Ghat\" is still surviving.\n\n== Educational institutes ==\n[[File:Agomani.JPG|thumb|Agomani Higher Secondary School]]\nEducational institutions of Agomani are :\n* [[Pragati College]] is premier college in Dhubri District.\n* [[Agomani Higher Secondary School]]; Founded in 1948 and Provincialised in 1977.\n* [[1476 No. Agomani J.B. School]]; Established in 1947.\n* [[1967 No. Bangla L.P. School]]; Established in 1971,\n* [[Kaldoba J.B. School]](Private); Established in 1985,\n[[Agomani Junior College,Agomani]]; Established in 2018\n*[[Sankardev shishu aru Bidya Niketan,Kaldoba]] Agomani(Shishu Shikha Samiti Assam,Guwahati)\n* [[Agomani Girls' M.E. School]]; Established in 1972,\n* [[Agomani Girls' High School]](Private); Established in 1980,\n*[[Lower Assam public School,Agomani]] (Private) CBSE\n* [[Agomani Jatiya Vidyalaya]](private);\n*[[Gurukul Adarshya Vidyalaya,Agomani]] (private) Digital school,\n*[[Dhubri Pollytechnic,Agomani]] it was senctioned,\n*[[Shernagar Jatiya Vidyalaya]] (private)Agomani,\n*[[Chilarai Academy,Agomani]] an english medium school(private)\n\n== Transport ==\nAgomani has a railway station named [[Agomani railway station]]. Two trains runs via this station. One train (Rajya Rani Express) runs three days in a week and another Train runs daily from [[Dhubri]] to [[New Jalpaiguri]] (Siliguri) (Inter City Express) via Agomani town.\nAgomani has a small bus stand. Air port facilities are available in the distance of 34.9 km named Rupshi Airport and 14.9 km distance from the district head quarter Dhubri Town.\n\n==Media==\n* [[Proma Cinema Hall]]\n [[File:Proma Cinema,Agomani.JPG|thumb|Talkies in Agomani Town]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Agomani}}\n{{Assam}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Dhubri district]]\n[[Category:Dhubri district]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the town in Dhubri District|its namesake district|Dhubri district}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2018}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{confusing|date=January 2015}}\n{{essay-like|date=January 2015}}\n{{more citations needed|date=January 2015}}\n}}\n\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Agomani\n| other_name                      = \n| nickname                        = \n| settlement_type                 = Town\n| image_skyline                   = \n| image_alt                       = \n| image_caption                   = \n| pushpin_map                     = India Assam#India\n| push