{"title_page": "Grindlay Peerless", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:1929 Grindlay Peerless 498cc Brooklands Hundred Model.jpg|thumb|300x300px|1929 Grindlay Peerless 498cc 'Hundred' Model.jpg]] -->\n\n[[File:Grindlay Peerless 1926 02 sports 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|1926 Grindlay Peerless]]\n'''Grindlay Peerless''' is a historic [[motorcycle]] manufacturer that operated out of [[Coventry]], England, throughout the early 20th-century, specialising in racing machines including the record breaking 498cc Grindlay Peerless.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://wiki.transport-museum.com/Default.aspx?Page=Grindlay-Peerless&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=Coventry Transport Museum}}</ref>\n\nAlthough a relatively short-lived [[marque]], Grindlay Peerless secured a number of high-profile achievements most notably that of works rider and tuner, Bill Lacey, achieving a [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme]] (FIM) world record by becoming the first man to exceed a 100 miles in an hour on British soil in August 1928 aboard his Grindlay Peerless.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/19163/lot/98/|title=Bonhams}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref> The company quickly became renowned for building powerful, high quality and technologically advanced machines.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.realclassic.co.uk/grindlay_peerless_100.html|title=www.realclassic.co.uk}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realclassic.co.uk/grindlaypeerlesstiger.html|title=www.realclassic.co.uk}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe very limited number of Grindlay Peerless machines produced means that they are now extremely rare.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/19768/lot/303/?keep_login_open=1|title=www.bonhams.com}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1910, following his departure from [[Riley Motor|Riley Cycle Company]], [[Alfred Robert Grindlay]] and his brother, William John Grindlay (a member of the highly exclusive ''Coventry and Country Club'') took over Coventry Motor & Sundries Co from William Edward Mann. The company was remodelled into Grindlay Sidecars, which originally began manufacturing body kits and sidecars in the early 1910s, and quickly became known for its \"extremely high quality\" machines.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Grindlay-Peerless|title=Grace's Guide to British Industrial History}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0YH4DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT122&lpg=PT122&dq=grindlay+sidecar&source=bl&ots=b6__LalnHs&sig=2elgMcKWCCLthRDDFL-AkSiHN4M&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi4tcO3jc_UAhXHfFAKHXXCD-Q4ChDoAQghMAA#v=onepage&q=grindlay%20sidecar&f=false|title=Classic British Motorcycles|last=Jackson|first=Colin|publisher=Fonthill Media|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://curve.coventry.ac.uk/open/file/e7fac4cd-1dbe-c86e-4df0-608d09016ad3/1/batchelorcomb.pdf|title=A Great munitions centre: Coventry's armaments and munitions industry 1914-1918}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/2749280.pdf|title=The Growth and Significance of the Coventry Car Component Industry, 1895-1939|last=Beaven|first=Bradley}}{{fv|date=July 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I|WWI]], Grindlay and Thomas Edward Musson combined their efforts to form the specialist sidecar manufacturer, Musson & Grindlay, operating out of Melbourne Works on Shakleton Road in [[Spon End]], [[Coventry]]. In 1923, following the dissolution of his partnership with Musson, Grindlay and Edward Peerless formed Grindlay Peerless.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The newly formed Grindlay Peerless operating out of Melbourne Works on Shakleton Road in [[Spon End]], [[Coventry]], entered into the wider motorcycle market and began making high-powered machines using [[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] (succeeded by [[Villiers Engineering|Villiers]]), [[Barr and Stroud|Barr & Stroud]], and later [[Rudge-Whitworth]] engines.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> Like the sidecars before them, the motorcycles not only had an exceptional standard of finish, including pressed monograms, elegantly shaped fuel tanks brightly plated with nickel and cadmium and luxury leather covered saddles, but were also recognised for their innovative design features. <ref name=\":5\" />\n\nWhile active Grindlay Peerless produced a large number of highly regarded motorcycles, including the record beating 498cc model, but by the mid 1930s the [[Great Depression]] caused production to reduce significantly and the company dissolved in 1939.<ref name=\"Gracesguide\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Grindlay-Peerless|title=www.gracesguide.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline ===\n* ''1923'' - [[Alfred Robert Grindlay]] and Edward Peerless form Grindlay Peerless<ref name=\"Gracesguide\"/>\n* ''1923'' - Grindlay Peerless 1000cc V-twin flagship model ([[Barr and Stroud|Barr & Stroud]] engine) released\n* ''1924'' - Grindlay Peerless 488cc single OHV model ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engine) released\n* ''1925'' - Grindlay Peerless 344cc, 346cc, 348cc ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engines) and 499cc sleeve-value models ([[Barr and Stroud|Barr & Stroud]] engine) released\n* ''1926'' - Racer Bill Lacey begins winning regularly on a tuned 344cc\n* ''1927'' - Manufacturing focuses on the more economical 344cc, 346cc and 488cc models ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engines) and production of the sleeve-value models ([[Barr and Stroud|Barr & Stroud]] engines) ceased\n* ''1927'' - Bill Lacey wins a [[Brooklands]] Gold Star Award on a 498cc Grindlay Peerless\n* ''1928'' - Grindlay Peerless 488cc model revised to 490cc and the Grindlay Peerless 677cc SV V-twin [[JA Prestwich Industries|(JAP engine]]) and 172cc two-stroke engines ([[Villiers Engineering|Villiers]] engine) released\n* ''1928'' - Bill Lacey sets the 500cc one-hour World and British record and 103.9 miles on a modified 498cc Grindlay Peerless\n* ''1929'' - Grindlay Peerless 500cc 'Hundred' Model ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engine) model released\n* ''1929'' - Bill Lacey sets a new 500cc one-hour World and British record at 105.87pmh\n* ''1929'' - Grindlay Peerless 490cc single OHV, 674cc single OHV and 750cc CV V-twin models ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engines) released\n* ''1930'' - Grindlay Peerless 196cc and 247cc two-stroke ([[Villiers Engineering|Villiers]] engines), 245cc OHV ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engine) and a number of variants of the 490cc OHV ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engine) models released\n* ''1931'' - Produced with all V-twin engines ceased with single JAP engines retained temporarily before being replaced by [[Rudge-Whitworth]] Python engines for the 348cc 499cc models\n* ''1932'' - Grindlay Peerless reduced their range of motorcycles to 3 models, the Tiger range, consisting of the light weight 250cc 'Tiger Cub', the mid range 499cc 'Tiger' and the top end 500cc 'Tiger Chief' and 'Tiger Chief TT' replica ([[Rudge-Whitworth]] engines)\n* ''1933'' - Variants on the Grindlay Peerless Tiger range released\n* ''1934'' - Grindlay Peerless limits motorcycle production and changes focus to other products\n* ''1939'' - Grindlay and Peerless part company\n\n=== The 'Hundred' Model ===\n[[File:Grindley Peerless Motorcycle (10643066516).jpg|thumb|Grindlay Peerless 'Hundred' Model. Brooklands Museum, Coventry]]\nFollowing Bill Lacey's record beating ride in 1929, Grindlay Peerless created a small number of replica motorcycles for sale to the public. The 500cc 'Hundred' model had JAP speedway engines and Webb forks as opposed to Lacey's personally tuned, twin-port engine and Brompton forks, however each motorcycle was individually tuned by Lacey's own mechanic, Wal Philips (1908 - 1998)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.classicmotorcycle.co.uk/the-phillips-injector/|title=www.classicmotorcycle.co.uk}}</ref>, and sold with a certificate guaranteeing Lacey had personally lapped the machine at [[Brooklands]] at 100mph. Of the 6 replicas produced only 2 are known to have survived.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sinlesscycles.com/index.php/present-sins/detail/1933-grindlay-peerless|title=www.sinlesscycles.com}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Technological Advances ===\nGrindlay Peerless adopted the use of sleeve-valve motors, a type of four-stroke engine more frequently used to power early aircraft, rather than the traditional side-valve engine, meaning that pushrods, value springs, rockers and cams were no longer required. The value operated system allowed for the spark plug to be repositioned for maximum efficiency, and required far less maintenance than a side-valve engine.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.realclassic.co.uk/grindlaypeerless.html|title=www.realclassic.co.uk|access-date=23 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527134948/http://www.realclassic.co.uk/grindlaypeerless.html|archive-date=27 May 2013|url-status=dead}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[List of Grindlay Peerless people]]\n* [[Alfred Robert Grindlay]]\n* [[History of Coventry|Historic Coventry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* Brooklands Museum - https://www.brooklandsmuseum.com/\n* Age of Diesel tribute to Grindlay Peerless - http://anyskin.tumblr.com/post/148784030057/1933-grindlay-peerless-305cc\n* Grindlay Peerless wins 'Best of Show Bikes' - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hU_DMUNDLIs\n* Victor Olson describes a Grindlay Peerless - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aoEozIGWOH0\n* Grindlay Peerless at VMCC Banbury Motorcycle Run 2016 - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oDXdVvPNZvo\n* 1933 Grindlay Peerless - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hBQIJHwJ2UM\n\n[[Category:Motorcycle manufacturers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Coventry motor companies]]\n[[Category:Defunct motorcycle manufacturers]]\n__INDEX__\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:1929 Grindlay Peerless 498cc Brooklands Hundred Model.jpg|thumb|300x300px|1929 Grindlay Peerless 498cc 'Hundred' Model.jpg]] -->\n\n[[File:Grindlay Peerless 1926 02 sports 1.jpg|thumb|upright=1.25|1926 Grindlay Peerless]]\n'''Grindlay Peerless''' is a historic [[motorcycle]] manufacturer that operated out of [[Coventry]], England, throughout the early 20th-century, specialising in racing machines including the record breaking 498cc Grindlay Peerless.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://wiki.transport-museum.com/Default.aspx?Page=Grindlay-Peerless&AspxAutoDetectCookieSupport=1|title=Coventry Transport Museum}}</ref>\n\nAlthough a relatively short-lived [[marque]], Grindlay Peerless secured a number of high-profile achievements most notably that of works rider and tuner, Bill Lacey, achieving a [[F\u00e9d\u00e9ration Internationale de Motocyclisme]] (FIM) world record by becoming the first man to exceed a 100 miles in an hour on British soil in August 1928 aboard his Grindlay Peerless.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/19163/lot/98/|title=Bonhams}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref> The company quickly became renowned for building powerful, high quality and technologically advanced machines.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.realclassic.co.uk/grindlay_peerless_100.html|title=www.realclassic.co.uk}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.realclassic.co.uk/grindlaypeerlesstiger.html|title=www.realclassic.co.uk}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe very limited number of Grindlay Peerless machines produced means that they are now extremely rare.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bonhams.com/auctions/19768/lot/303/?keep_login_open=1|title=www.bonhams.com}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nIn 1910, following his departure from [[Riley Motor|Riley Cycle Company]], [[Alfred Robert Grindlay]] and his brother, William John Grindlay (a member of the highly exclusive ''Coventry and Country Club'') took over Coventry Motor & Sundries Co from William Edward Mann. The company was remodelled into Grindlay Sidecars, which originally began manufacturing body kits and sidecars in the early 1910s, and quickly became known for its \"extremely high quality\" machines.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Grindlay-Peerless|title=Grace's Guide to British Industrial History}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=0YH4DQAAQBAJ&pg=PT122&lpg=PT122&dq=grindlay+sidecar&source=bl&ots=b6__LalnHs&sig=2elgMcKWCCLthRDDFL-AkSiHN4M&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi4tcO3jc_UAhXHfFAKHXXCD-Q4ChDoAQghMAA#v=onepage&q=grindlay%20sidecar&f=false|title=Classic British Motorcycles|last=Jackson|first=Colin|publisher=Fonthill Media|year=2013|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://curve.coventry.ac.uk/open/file/e7fac4cd-1dbe-c86e-4df0-608d09016ad3/1/batchelorcomb.pdf|title=A Great munitions centre: Coventry's armaments and munitions industry 1914-1918}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://core.ac.uk/download/pdf/2749280.pdf|title=The Growth and Significance of the Coventry Car Component Industry, 1895-1939|last=Beaven|first=Bradley}}{{fv|date=July 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[World War I|WWI]], Grindlay and Thomas Edward Musson combined their efforts to form the specialist sidecar manufacturer, Musson & Grindlay, operating out of Melbourne Works on Shakleton Road in [[Spon End]], [[Coventry]]. In 1923, following the dissolution of his partnership with Musson, Grindlay and Edward Peerless formed Grindlay Peerless.<ref name=\":4\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> The newly formed Grindlay Peerless operating out of Melbourne Works on Shakleton Road in [[Spon End]], [[Coventry]], entered into the wider motorcycle market and began making high-powered machines using [[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] (succeeded by [[Villiers Engineering|Villiers]]), [[Barr and Stroud|Barr & Stroud]], and later [[Rudge-Whitworth]] engines.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":7\" /> Like the sidecars before them, the motorcycles not only had an exceptional standard of finish, including pressed monograms, elegantly shaped fuel tanks brightly plated with nickel and cadmium and luxury leather covered saddles, but were also recognised for their innovative design features. <ref name=\":5\" />\n\nWhile active Grindlay Peerless produced a large number of highly regarded motorcycles, including the record beating 498cc model, but by the mid 1930s the [[Great Depression]] caused production to reduce significantly and the company dissolved in 1939.<ref name=\"Gracesguide\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.gracesguide.co.uk/Grindlay-Peerless|title=www.gracesguide.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n=== Timeline ===\n* ''1923'' - [[Alfred Robert Grindlay]] and Edward Peerless form Grindlay Peerless<ref name=\"Gracesguide\"/>\n* ''1923'' - Grindlay Peerless 1000cc V-twin flagship model ([[Barr and Stroud|Barr & Stroud]] engine) released\n* ''1924'' - Grindlay Peerless 488cc single OHV model ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engine) released\n* ''1925'' - Grindlay Peerless 344cc, 346cc, 348cc ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engines) and 499cc sleeve-value models ([[Barr and Stroud|Barr & Stroud]] engine) released\n* ''1926'' - Racer Bill Lacey begins winning regularly on a tuned 344cc\n* ''1927'' - Manufacturing focuses on the more economical 344cc, 346cc and 488cc models ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engines) and production of the sleeve-value models ([[Barr and Stroud|Barr & Stroud]] engines) ceased\n* ''1927'' - Bill Lacey wins a [[Brooklands]] Gold Star Award on a 498cc Grindlay Peerless\n* ''1928'' - Grindlay Peerless 488cc model revised to 490cc and the Grindlay Peerless 677cc SV V-twin [[JA Prestwich Industries|(JAP engine]]) and 172cc two-stroke engines ([[Villiers Engineering|Villiers]] engine) released\n* ''1928'' - Bill Lacey sets the 500cc one-hour World and British record and 103.9 miles on a modified 498cc Grindlay Peerless\n* ''1929'' - Grindlay Peerless 500cc 'Hundred' Model ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engine) model released\n* ''1929'' - Bill Lacey sets a new 500cc one-hour World and British record at 105.87pmh\n* ''1929'' - Grindlay Peerless 490cc single OHV, 674cc single OHV and 750cc CV V-twin models ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engines) released\n* ''1930'' - Grindlay Peerless 196cc and 247cc two-stroke ([[Villiers Engineering|Villiers]] engines), 245cc OHV ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engine) and a number of variants of the 490cc OHV ([[JA Prestwich Industries|JAP]] engine) models released\n* ''1931'' - Produced with all V-twin engines ceased with single JAP engines retained temporarily before being replaced by [[Rudge-Whitworth]] Python engines for the 348cc 499cc models\n* ''1932'' - Grindlay Peerless reduced their range of motorcycles to 3 models, the Tiger range, consisting of the light weight 250cc 'Tiger Cub', the mid range 499cc 'Tiger' and the top end 500cc 'Tiger Chief' and 'Tiger Chief TT' replica ([[Rudge-Whitworth]] engines)\n* ''1933'' - Variants on the Grindlay Peerless Tiger range released\n* ''1934'' - Grindlay Peerless limits motorcycle production and changes focus to other products\n* ''1939'' - Grindlay and Peerless part company\n\n=== The 'Hundred' Model ===\n[[File:Grindley Peerless Motorcycle (10643066516).jpg|thumb|Grindlay Peerless 'Hundred' Model. Brooklands Museum, Coventry]]\nFollowing Bill Lacey's record beating ride in 1929, Grindlay Peerless created a small number of replica motorcycles for sale to the public. The 500cc 'Hundred' model had JAP speedway engines and Webb forks as opposed to Lacey's personally tuned, twin-port engine and Brompton forks, however each motorcycle was individually tuned by Lacey's own mechanic, Wal Philips (1908 - 1998)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.classicmotorcycle.co.uk/the-phillips-injector/|title=www.classicmotorcycle.co.uk}}</ref>, and sold with a certificate guaranteeing Lacey had personally lapped the machine at [[Brooklands]] at 100mph. Of the 6 replicas produced only 2 are known to have survived.<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sinlesscycles.com/index.php/present-sins/detail/1933-grindlay-peerless|title=www.sinlesscycles.com}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Technological Advances ===\nGrindlay Peerless adopted the use of sleeve-valve motors, a type of four-stroke engine more frequently used to power early aircraft, rather than the traditional side-valve engine, meaning that pushrods, value springs, rockers and cams were no longer required. The value operated system allowed for the spark plug to be repositioned for maximum efficiency, and required far less maintenance than a side-valve engine.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.realclassic.co.uk/grindlaypeerless.html|title=www.realclassic.co.uk|access-date=23 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130527134948/http://www.realclassic.co.uk/grindlaypeerless.html|archive-date=27 May 2013|url-status=dead}}{{Better source|date=January 2018}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Notable persons associated with Grindlay Peerless]]\n* [[Alfred Robert Grindlay]]\n* [[History of Coventry|Historic Coventry]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* Brooklands Museum - https://www.brooklandsmuseum.com/\n* Age of Diesel tribute to Grindlay Peerless - http://anyskin.tumblr.com/post/148784030057/1933-grindlay-peerless-305cc\n* Grindlay Peerless wins 'Best of Show Bikes' - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hU_DMUNDLIs\n* Victor Olson describes a Grindlay Peerless - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aoEozIGWOH0\n* Grindlay Peerless at VMCC Banbury Motorcycle Run 2016 - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=oDXdVvPNZvo\n* 1933 Grindlay Peerless - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hBQIJHwJ2UM\n\n[[Category:Motorcycle manufacturers of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Coventry motor companies]]\n[[Category:Defunct motorcycle manufacturers]]\n__INDEX__\n", "name_user": "AndrewFletcher", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSee also", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Grindlay_Peerless"}
